  <datafield tag="500" ind1=" " ind2=" ">
    <subfield code="a">The Rev. May and his wife dined with William Lloyd Garrison at Lydia Mott&apos;s. Mrs. Mayo believes in spiritualism. Garrison left Albany in the pouring rain; the Hudson River rose six feet. The temperature changed drastically and it was cold in the train from Syracuse to Rochester. Garrison is now in Isaac Post&apos;s parlor. Charles L. Remond and sister are also here. There is considerable disappointment at Parker Pillsbury&apos;s absence. Garrison comments: &quot;[Frederick] Douglass, I am told, intends to show fight, but I trust and advise that no reply may be made to any thing he may say of us.&quot;</subfield>
